@node IFF
Load an IFF image
=================


A file requester will appear when this option is clicked.  You should select 
an IFF picture to load.  If it is not an IFF file then a requester will 
appear informing you of this fact.  If you wish to cancel, then just click 
Cancel on the file requester.  When the image has loaded, it will be
displayed on-screen with an information bar giving the filename, size and
the number of colours.
@endnode
@node ABK

Load an ABK image
=================


This option is identical to the first option in the menu but instead it
will load an ABK image, which is the standard that was introduced with AMOS.
It provides much better compression than a normal IFF file, often halving
the size of the file.
@endnode
@node SABK

Load a squashed ABK image
=========================


Again, this option is identical to the other Load operators.  This option
loads a squashed memory bank, offering huge differences of size over a
standard IFF file.
@endnode
@node PPABK

Load Powerpacked ABK image
==========================


Need I say it again?  'Identical to the other Load operators'.  This will
load a memory bank compressed with Powerpacker, the premier Amiga
compression program.  This method offers even better results than the
squashed ABK image, although there is not much gain.
@endnode
@node SCREEN

Pack as screen
==============


You need to select this option if you want to save out in any of the ABK
formats.  If you're going to use the Save IFF image option, then you do
not need to pack your image.  This option will save the image data, and
the size and position of the screen it occupies.
@endnode
@node BITMAP

Pack as bitmap
==============


This option is very similar to the Pack as screen option but it only saves
the image data.  This means the file will be smaller than an ABK file with
all the screen data.
@endnode
@node SAVEIFF

Save IFF image
==============


This option can only be selected when there is an image held in memory.
The image will be saved out as a standard IFF picture which can be loaded
into any art package such as Brilliance, Personal Paint and Deluxe Paint.
@endnode
@node SAVEABK

Save ABK image
==============


Saves the image as an ABK picture which can be loaded into a 'memory bank'
in AMOS.  The files are often much smaller than their IFF counterparts.
The image must first be packed using either the 'Pack as Screen' and
'Pack as Bitmap' options.
@endnode
@node SAVESABK

Save squashed ABK image
=======================


Saves the image as a squashed ABK picture which is even smaller than a
normal ABK file.  The image must first be packed before you can use this
option.  See 'Save ABK image'.
@endnode
@node SAVEPPABK

Save Powerpacked ABK image
==========================


Similar to the squashed ABK image but uses the popular Powerpacker library.
Please refer to the option 'Save ABK image'.
@endnode
@node ABOUT

About
=====


Displays information about this program and included a current memory
status.
@endnode
@node QUIT

Quit
====


Leaves the Image Compressor.
@endnode

@node PROG

The Image Compressor is aimed at all AMOS programmers.  It is a simple
utility to compress and convert images into different formats.  It was
written to replace the IFF Compactor that is supplied with AMOS
Professional.

In my version you can squash and Powerpack ABK images.  The main
limitation with the IFF Compactor was that you could only convert IFF
files to ABK, you couldn't do the reverse.

To Powerpack an ABK image, you must have the powerpacker.library in
the LIBS: assign, either on your boot disk or a hard drive.
@endnode

@node FUTURE

It is my aim to develop this program into a far more capable beast.
The full version will be Licenceware when it is released hopefully.
It will feature:

· On-line hypertext help.
· Batch conversion of images.
· Thumbnails.
· Preferences screen to change the level of compression.
· Palette optimizer.  Quite often people choose more colours than is
  necessary to draw their pictures.  This function will compute the
  actual amount of colours in the image and change the screen mode
  accordingly.
· And all your good ideas.

If you have any ideas which you think would make Image Compressor a more
useful program, or if you have any bugs, then write to me.  My address is:


